- [x] multi-level / jump to next level on end of level — reaching `return` now auto-loads the next parsable file in the tree (depth-first, dirs-first) instead of ending the run, carrying health/ammo across; only shows the win screen on the last file [Task 22]
- [x] add languages: asm, js, ts, python, java, c++, objc (and other realworld languages, as long as supported by our libs - we dont want to use multiple libs for that) — added JS, TS/TSX, Python, Java, C++, Go, Rust, Ruby, C#, Bash, Scala, Objective-C via one generic Tree-sitter-driven adapter (still just tree-sitter, no second parsing lib); no ASM (no ABI-compatible prebuilt grammar found), Kotlin/Lua skipped (no prebuilt wasm shipped by their packages) [Task 23]
- [x] ensure code parser only acts on actual supported code, in case some troll loads his meme folder or whatever. ensure that loaded code is never executed. — strict extension whitelist (only registered adapters' extensions reach a parser at all), plus a size cap + binary-content sniff on top; loaded text is only ever fed to `Parser.parse()` (builds an AST), never eval'd/compiled/run; any parse failure now logs a warning and skips the file instead of crashing the map generator or game loop [Task 23]
- [x] map top left should be semi-transparent. player and direction should be more clearly visible, same for the exit. enemies shouldnt be show until the room was entered. — always-on minimap now uses a semi-transparent dark rgba backing panel, a bright solid triangle for the player's exact position/facing, a pulsing high-contrast exit marker, and enemies stay hidden until the player's collision box AABB-intersects their room (sticky once discovered) [Task 24]
- [x] more traps (kinds, but also placement) — added timed spike traps (tile toggles safe/damaging on a per-trap cycle) and invisible proximity mines (reveal + detonate for AoE damage if you linger, timer resets if you back off in time), both scattered procedurally at 1-tile-wide corridor choke points rather than open room floor. Not exhaustive — more kinds/placement variety is still open for later [Task 24]
- [x] if the AST has a detectable entrypoint (like `main()` for c, index.php for PHP etc), use that a starting level after loading the workspace — workspace load now searches for a standard entrypoint filename (main.c/cpp/py/go/rs, index.php, index.js, Program.cs, etc.) across the whole tree, falling back to a content-based `main()` function scan for the C family, and auto-launches it immediately; falls back further to the first parsable file in tree order if nothing matches [Task 24]
- [x] mines need to be visible way earlier, its almost impossible to avoid them — sight radius (visible) and fuse-arming radius (actually dangerous) are now separate: mines reveal from 4.5 tiles away but only start their fuse within 1.8, giving real reaction room. Also added the ability to shoot a spotted mine to disarm it outright — safe from beyond its blast radius, but still hurts point-blank — since spotting one you can't do anything about wasn't useful
- [x] drop, enemies, exit etc should be in front based on drawing distance from POV - for example: sometimes a dropped item next to exit "disappears" behind the exit — every world billboard (enemies, projectiles, keys, ammo drops, exit marker, teleporters, decorations, mines) is now collected into one list and drawn in a single depth-sorted pass (furthest-to-nearest), instead of each category drawing in a fixed order regardless of actual distance [Task 25]
- [x] canvas looses focus on level change - bug — `canvas.focus()` is now called right after the canvas is attached to the DOM on every level (re)load, so WASD works immediately without an extra click first [Task 25]
- [x] ensure the player spawns far enough outside the aggro range of any enemy, except that's not possible without leaving the room — spawn now picks whichever corner of the first room has the greatest minimum distance to any enemy-bearing room's center, instead of a fixed corner; best-effort (small/dense levels may still have no fully safe corner), but strictly better than before [Task 25]
- [x] pause game if canvas not focussed / ESC was pressed — window blur now forces a pause (and Escape toggles one explicitly), freezing the sim and drawing a "PAUSED" overlay over one frozen frame; click or a second Escape resumes. Distinct from the existing Tab automap pause [Task 25]
- [x] fullscreen support for the canvas — F toggles the Fullscreen API on the canvas, called directly from the keydown handler (required for browsers to accept it as a real user gesture) [Task 25]
- [x] level start screen - showing stats about AST and the resulting lvl (enemy, room etc count). if there is a detectable project name of the loaded workspace: use that as "campaign" name, if not: use directory name except its `src`, in that case use the upper level directory name. use the filename as level name. game should be paused till the player ack's that screen. Also add a "Commit Summary" (Level End Screen) showing stats like "X Lines refactored, Y Bugs squashed". — both overlays added, blocking play until acknowledged. Campaign name = workspace root name; the "parent dir if named src" fallback isn't reachable in a browser sandbox (the File System Access API only grants a handle to the picked directory itself, no way to walk up to its parent) so a root literally named "src" just uses "src" as-is — documented in code. Commit summary shows the cleared file's line count and a new per-level kill counter [Task 26]
- [x] save & quit (campaign persistence) — save the current campaign state (current file, HP, ammo, score, weapons) to `localStorage`. add a "Continue Run" button in the main menu for navigating massive repositories over multiple sessions. — autosaves (throttled during play, immediately on level transitions) to localStorage; "Continue Run" button re-picks the workspace (file handles can't be persisted across sessions) and resumes at the saved path with carried-over health/ammo/weapon, falling back to a fresh entrypoint launch if the saved file isn't found. Cleared on death or campaign completion [Task 26]
- [x] enemy stuck in or on a wall — first-in-pack spawns and random pack-member/roam positions could land exactly on a tile boundary (room-center math wasn't floored) or, in labyrinth/maze rooms, anywhere in the room's bounding rectangle including wall tiles; only the single tile under the raw position got force-cleared, so a straddling collision box could still overlap an uncleared neighbor. Every candidate spawn/roam position is now snapped to its containing tile's exact center first, guaranteeing the enemy's collision box stays fully inside the one tile that does get cleared
- [x] aggro picks up through wall, should be line of sight only (or when shot) — proximity aggro now requires an unobstructed line of sight (reusing the same ray-sampling check ranged enemy fire already used) in addition to being in range; damage aggro (getting shot) still bypasses it entirely, since being hit at all proves you've been spotted [Task 27]
- [x] player needs an unlimited meelee weapon ("SIGKILL Knife" / "Refactoring Crowbar") to be able to continue when out of ammo until dead or looting ammo. should feature a small lifesteal effect (+1 HP) or force a guaranteed ammo drop on kill to encourage aggressive play — added as weapon slot 3: 0 ammo cost, only connects within 1.5 tiles regardless of what's aimed at further away, heals +1 stability per kill. (Every kill already dropped ammo unconditionally, so the "guaranteed drop" half was already covered game-wide.) [Task 27]
- [x] weapons should have a range determined by their type (or realistic equivalent) — hitscan weapons should use a "Cone of Fire" (spread angle that widens with distance) instead of a hard drop-off to 0 damage — ranged pellets (pistol/shotgun) now get a random column deviation scaled to the z-buffer depth of whatever's downrange, so a shot lined up on something far away can still miss, while point-blank shots stay accurate; melee is exempt (it can't reach that far to begin with). No weapon previously had any range cutoff at all, so this replaces "unlimited perfect accuracy" rather than an actual drop-off [Task 27]
- [x] acid pools look almost the same as the exit on the minimap, needs differantiaton — acid tiles recolored to a hot amber/orange (`#ff9d1f`) on both the always-on HUD minimap and the full Tab automap (which, it turned out, wasn't rendering hazard tiles distinctly at all — they fell through to the plain-floor case), so neither can be confused with the green pulsing exit marker [Task 27]
- [x] more weapons, to be randomly dropped by enemies. Like a rocket-like-launcher for AoE damage, or an MP. — added the MP (fully automatic, high fire rate/low damage) and Rocket Launcher (slow real projectile, AoE splash, self-damage included) as weapon slots 4/5. Neither is owned from the start — only an Elite kill's guaranteed drop unlocks one, so "randomly dropped by enemies" is scoped to Elites specifically rather than any kill (a deliberate call: making them freely available from the start would make the drop meaningless) [Task 28]
- [x] each weapon should use unique ammo, also resulting in a slightly but noticeable different tracer — ammo split into two pools (Bullets: pistol/shotgun/MP, Rockets: launcher only); every weapon now has its own tracer color (yellow pistol, orange-ish shotgun, silver knife slash, blue MP, orange rocket) [Task 28]
- [x] ammo should also be randomly placed across maps for player pickup, only as a sparse backup - primary source should be spawn + loot. — `placeAmmoPickups` scatters a sparse handful of bullets/rockets pickups across non-spawn rooms at generation time, mostly bullets with rockets rarer [Task 28]
- [x] weapon should be rendered differently, depending on their type/strength — every weapon (including the pre-existing pistol/shotgun/knife) now has its own distinct bottom-of-screen silhouette instead of one generic reused blaster shape: boxy single-barrel pistol, wider double-barrel shotgun, an actually-connected blade+handle knife, a slim long-barreled MP with a stick mag, and a big shoulder-mounted rocket tube [Task 28]
- [x] collectible health and armor drops (randomly dropped on top of ammo by enemies) — regular enemy kills now roll a weighted random drop (bullets/rockets/health/armor); armor is a new player stat, absorbed 1:1 before health on any hit, capped at 100 [Task 28]
- [x] elite enemies / bosses — instead of just spawning *more* enemies (complexity packs), functions with extreme cyclomatic complexity (e.g., massive legacy controllers) spawn a single Elite Enemy (different tint/sprite, 4x HP, high damage, guaranteed weapon drop). — functions at/above complexity 40 (exactly where a pack would otherwise hit its biggest size) spawn one Elite instead: 1.5x sprite scale, a gold tint/HP-bar/label, 4x a single enemy's HP at that complexity, 2x melee/ranged damage. Death guarantees either a still-unowned MP/Rocket Launcher or a large (50) health pack once both are owned [Task 28]
- [x] secret rooms (Secrets) — parse AST for "Dead Code" (unreachable code, blocks after returns) or large comment blocks. generate these as hidden rooms off the main map, accessible via fake walls, containing high-value loot (mega-health, rocket ammo). — unreachable statements after a `return` (C/PHP/generic adapters) each carve a small room behind a fake wall tile that looks and blocks exactly like a normal wall; opening one drops a guaranteed mega-health or fat rockets pickup inside [Task 29]. Follow-up: made purely 100% indistinguishable was too obscure to ever realistically find — fake walls now carry a very slight cool hue nudge off the real wall color (3D scene, minimap, and automap all use the same tiny tint) so a player who looks closely has a real shot at spotting one
- [x] lore terminals — parse code comments (`//` or `/* */`) into interactable glowing wall textures. pressing 'E' opens a text popup with the original code comment. — large comments become glowing wall tiles near the room they came from; interacting nearby pauses the game and shows the raw comment text. Uses R, not E — E is already the turn-right key in this game's Q/E-turn scheme (see [[feedback-control-scheme]]) [Task 29]. Follow-up: a long comment could overflow the overlay box with no way to read the rest — the box now caps its own height and holding W/S scrolls the wrapped text, with a scrollbar shown only when it actually overflows
- [x] by accident, header files (.h) make nice bonus levels for restocking ammo. lets visually differentiate them from normal source levels. loot chances / drops should be slightly higher as well, since its a single closed room with at least one enemy — `.h` files now generate with a distinct cool steel/teal wall+floor theme, a boosted static-pickup rate/amount, and enemy kills lean toward scarcer/higher-value drops [Task 29]
- [x] if not fullscreen: show console log near to the canvas, randomly drop hints about traps being near and similar — a DOM sidebar next to the canvas mirrors `console.log` and occasionally drops a random in-character hint while a level is running; hidden automatically while the canvas is fullscreen (a DOM sibling can't render in that state) [Task 29]. Follow-up: raw object dumps (e.g. logging a whole `ParsedFile`/`GameMap`) ruined the effect and readability — the sidebar now only ever mirrors an actual string message (an object-only call is dropped entirely, a trailing object after a string message is ignored, not stringified), and any surviving line is length-capped. Second follow-up: the per-level `[map] ...` log line printed the exit tile's exact coordinates in plain text — a spoiler the sidebar then mirrored verbatim; removed from the printed string (the full map object is still passed through for devtools inspection, which takes a deliberate click to expand, not a passive read)
- [x] avoid pixelation at fullscreen — `.scene-canvas` and `.scene-canvas:fullscreen` both now declare `image-rendering: crisp-edges` (fallback) then `pixelated` explicitly, rather than relying purely on cascade inheritance into the `:fullscreen` state [Task 30]
- [x] mousewheel weapon switching (shoulder keys on gamepad) — the mousewheel now cycles through owned, non-melee weapons (wrapping), bound to the canvas so it never hijacks scrolling the file-tree/console sidebar. Gamepad shoulder-key support not implemented at the time — no gamepad support existed in this engine yet at all (see the general gamepad/joystick support entry below, added in [Task 33]) [Task 30]
- [x] melee weapon can be used with LEFT CTRL, dont add it to the weapon list / number hotkeys — the SIGKILL Knife is now unreachable via number keys or the mousewheel (excluded by its own `meleeRange` field, not a hardcoded slot) and is bound exclusively to Left-Ctrl as an instant "quick-melee" swing: a pure viewmodel overlay independent of whatever ranged weapon is equipped — `weaponIndex`, `ownedWeapons`, and the HUD ammo label never change [Task 30]
- [x] option for gorelevel, which controls the amount of blood effects. normal/default is current state, add "no gore", "more gore" and "extreme gore" options on top. — a Gore dropdown in the sidebar (None/Normal/More/Extreme = 0x/1x/3x/10x) persisted to localStorage, scaling blood-particle count, rendered size, and how long a landed particle lingers as a floor stain (a genuinely new concept — previously every particle vanished under a second regardless of whether it had landed) [Task 30]. Follow-up: Extreme (10x) reads as over-the-top in practice — hidden from the dropdown for now behind `EXTREME_GORE_ENABLED = false` in effects.ts (same disable-behind-a-flag pattern as `DECORATIONS_ENABLED`); a previously-saved "extreme" preference downgrades to "more" instead. Also found and fixed a real, previously-shipped bug while verifying this: `GORE_KEY`'s `const` was declared below the point where `loadGoreLevel()` was first called, so every read hit its temporal-dead-zone, threw, got silently swallowed by an empty `catch`, and the Gore setting never actually persisted across a reload — it always silently reset to Normal regardless of what was saved
- [x] fps (if possible: also gpu/cpu usage) display, toggable - default off. use RIGHT_CTRL as hotkey (for now) — Right-Ctrl toggles a top-right FPS + frame-time readout (averaged twice a second, from the real unclamped frame delta so a stutter doesn't get invisibly floored by the sim's own dt clamp), visible across every render state including the automap/pause/lore overlays. GPU/CPU usage not implemented — no standard browser API exposes that to page JS in a sandboxed context [Task 30]
- [x] name mp5 "gdb" and rocket launcher "ghidra" — renamed in weapons.ts's WEAPONS array (only the display `name` field; array indices/ammo/behavior unchanged), plus every doc comment, hint caption, and console-sidebar hint that referenced the old names [Task 31]
- [x] cone of fire / distance spread is a bit extreme — the aim-deviation formula is now quadratic in range (scaled by `(range/FOG_FAR)²`) instead of linear, so medium-range shots stay noticeably tighter and only the true maximum visual range (where the world fades to black anyway) spreads as much as before [Task 31]
- [x] Forced weapon unlock for MP at the 4th level, 8th for rocket launcher (in a campaign only) — a 1-based campaign level counter (persisted in the campaign save) force-adds gdb/ghidra to `ownedWeapons` once reached, regardless of whether an Elite ever dropped them; never removes anything, so an already-looted weapon is unaffected. Only advances via the auto-chain (`advanceToNextLevel`), not manual sidebar picks [Task 31]
- [x] code smell detection to increase complexity and/or difficulty — functions with >5 parameters or >3 nesting levels now get bonus complexity points (scaled by how far over the threshold, not a flat penalty), added on top of the normal decision-point score in all three parser paths (C, PHP, generic). A smelly function ends up tougher (or spawns as an Elite at extreme complexity) same as genuinely complex control flow already did [Task 31]
- [x] option for difficulty — an Easy/Normal/Hard sidebar dropdown (persisted to localStorage) scales enemy HP (0.7x/1x/1.5x, rescaled in-place on the map's Enemy objects at engine construction), enemy-dealt damage (melee/ranged only, not traps/hazards/self-splash), and ammo/health/armor pickup amounts (1.3x/1x/0.7x, inverse of HP — harder difficulty is scarcer too, not just tougher) [Task 31]
- [x] scoring (HUD has a Score slot since Task 20, always 0 — no scoring logic yet), extra points for health, ammo left, path length (shorter = better) and time needed (faster = better) at end of level, plus points for every kill (depending on enemy). score malus at end of level for health below 100% — `src/engine/scoring.ts`: points per kill scaled by the killed entity's `complexityScore` (tripled for an Elite), plus bonuses for remaining health/ammo (against what the level started you with), completion speed (maxed at/under 90s, decaying to 0 by 180s), and route efficiency (actual distance walked vs. a new BFS-shortest spawn→exit tile distance on `GameMap`), minus a malus scaled to how far below full health you finished. Recomputed live every frame (cheap, pure function) so the HUD's Score readout is a running projection, final the instant the exit is reached [Task 32]
- [x] persisted highscore list — top-10 board in `localStorage` (`src/engine/highscores.ts`), best score first, viewable via a new sidebar "Highscores" button opening a `<dialog>` (Score/Campaign/Level/Hash table) [Task 32]. Follow-up: recording on *every* level clear was too noisy for a multi-level campaign — an entry is now only written once a run actually ends, on death (`onGameOver`, which now also carries final stats, same as `onWin` already did) or on finishing the whole campaign (`advanceToNextLevel`'s "no more files" branch), never on an ordinary mid-campaign level clear. Each entry also now records `levelsCleared` (how many levels were actually cleared before the run ended — `campaignLevelIndex - 1` on death since the level died on wasn't cleared, `campaignLevelIndex` on completion since it was), shown as its own "Levels" column
- [x] user pickable bgm folder — needs a simple settings menu for volume control (Master, SFX, BGM) so custom music doesn't overpower game audio — `audio.ts`'s single master gain split into independent SFX and BGM buses under one master; three sidebar sliders (persisted to localStorage) control all three. `src/engine/bgm.ts` picks a local folder via the File System Access API and plays its `.mp3`/`.ogg`/`.wav` files back as a shuffled, looping playlist through an `<audio>` element routed into the BGM bus (streamed, not fully decoded up front, so a large file doesn't have to load whole) [Task 32]
- [x] scoresystem should also store a hash (sha256 or similar) of the AST, or code scanned. this should also be displayed in the highscore list, for comparison. part of that hash should be based on the campaign/project name. — each recorded run hashes `JSON.stringify(parsed AST) + campaignName` with `crypto.subtle.digest('SHA-256', ...)`; the truncated hex digest is shown in the Highscores dialog (full hash in the cell's tooltip) [Task 32]
- [x] canvas should scale to viewport in windowed mode — `.scene-canvas` now also caps `max-height: 100vh` (previously only bounded by width) with `object-fit: contain`, so a short/narrow window can no longer derive a height taller than the viewport and clip the bottom of the scene; letterboxed instead of clipped [Task 33]
- [x] compass pointing to the exit — a small dial below the always-on minimap (`drawCompass` in `hud.ts`) with a needle computed from the angle between the player's position and the exit tile, rotated relative to the player's own facing so it reads correctly no matter which way they're looking — same convention as the automap's player marker [Task 33]. Follow-up: disabled again behind `COMPASS_ENABLED = false` in `hud.ts` — the needle read as inverted on at least one axis, and the dial didn't fit visually next to the minimap; code is intact, just gated, pending a fix/redesign. Second follow-up: root cause was the needle's rest (bearing-zero) geometry pointing along local +X ("east"/3 o'clock) instead of -Y ("up"/12 o'clock) — a target dead ahead should read as "up", not sideways, and basing it on +X put the whole left/right sweep 90° off from what a glance expects. Fixed the geometry (verified against a synthetic map in headless Chromium: dead-ahead→up, behind→down, right→right, left→left, screenshot confirmed) and redesigned placement — `renderMinimap` now returns its panel's bounding rect and the needle draws directly in its top-right corner instead of as a separate floating dial. Re-enabled (`COMPASS_ENABLED = true`) [Task 34]
- [x] bonus score points for reading lore panels + exploring >95% of the map — `scoring.ts` gains two new bonuses: a flat 100pts per unique lore terminal read (tracked in a `Set` keyed by tile), and a 750pt "100% Clear" bonus once unique walkable tiles visited crosses 95% of the level's total walkable tiles (counted once at level start; secret rooms stay excluded from that denominator, so finding them is a bonus, not a requirement) [Task 33]
- [x] ammo to scarce on normal difficultiy — static map ammo pickups bumped ~40-50% (bullets 8→11, rockets 2→3, all difficulties), and Normal specifically now rolls enemy loot kind against a slightly ammo-favoring weight table (Easy/Hard already have their own scarcity curve via the existing per-drop amount multiplier, so only Normal's drop-*kind* odds changed) [Task 33]
- [x] gamepad/joystick support — `InputController.pollGamepad()` polls the HTML5 Gamepad API once per frame (no axis/button change events exist to listen for instead): left stick moves/strafes, right stick turns, RT/R2 fires (edge-triggered like a click, plus held for automatic weapons), bumpers cycle weapons (reusing the existing mousewheel-cycle queue), R3 or B triggers quick-melee. All blended additively with existing keyboard/mouse input, so both work at the same time [Task 33]
- [x] dont close end-game dialog on fire, happens by accident all the time in a fight — every blocking overlay (`GameHud.show()`: level-start briefing, commit summary, Kernel Panic, Build Successful) now ignores its own dismiss triggers (Enter/Space/Escape, mousedown, and any gamepad button) for 1.2s after it appears, so mashing the fire button in the fight that triggered it can't instantly close it before it's even readable. Also added a gamepad dismiss path (polled directly via `requestAnimationFrame`, since no engine `InputController` is running while these overlays are up) — previously a gamepad-only player had no way to dismiss them at all [Task 34]
- [x] console hints often come twice in a row, shouldnt happen. each hint should be different to the previous — `consoleSidebar.ts` now tracks `lastHintIndex` and re-rolls (in a `while` loop) whenever the random pick matches it [Task 34]
- [x] cone-of-fire still to extreme — reduced the base max deviation (56px → 38px) and changed the range falloff from quadratic to cubic (`(range/FOG_FAR)³`), so medium-range pistol/gdb shots stay reliable and only the last stretch before `FOG_FAR` spreads noticeably [Task 35]
- [x] compass shouldnt overlay the minimap, add a little cutout in the border to contain it in — `renderMinimap` now reserves a dedicated, separately-bordered notch in the panel's bottom-right gutter, entirely outside the grid-drawing area; the compass needle draws centered in that notch instead of overlapping the grid corner. Verified in headless Chromium against both a large and a small map [Task 35]
- [x] optional replay storage at end of level (even possible?), and a replay player obv. highscores should include a replay as well that can be replayed — deterministic replay system: `Math.random()` replaced with a seeded mulberry32 PRNG (`src/prng.ts`, extracted from the map generator's existing seeded approach) everywhere gameplay-outcome-relevant randomness happens — enemy AI roam/fire-cooldown timing, loot rolls, weapon cone-of-fire spread, elite-loot coinflip — while purely cosmetic randomness (blood particles, SFX pitch, BGM shuffle, console hints) stays on `Math.random()` since it never feeds back into simulation state. Each level launch records a fresh gameplay seed plus every frame's digested input (`InputController.captureSnapshot()`, a non-destructive peek) via `ReplayRecorder`, capped at ~6 minutes of frames; whichever level's recording is live when a run ends gets attached to that run's highscore entry. A new "Watch Replay" button per highscore entry (only shown for entries that have one) re-picks the workspace (same pattern as Continue Run), verifies the re-parsed file's AST hash still matches before trusting it to regenerate the map, then drives a fresh `RaycasterEngine` with the recorded seed and a `ReplayPlaybackInput` standing in for live input, frame-by-frame. Scoped to a single level (the one the run ended on), not a full multi-level campaign replay — an R&D feature, not a complete solution. Verified deterministic (same seed + inputs → byte-identical end stats) against the real engine/enemyAi/loot code in headless Chromium [Task 35]. Follow-up: expanded to cover the *whole* campaign run, not just the level it ended on — `ReplayRecorder` replaced with `CampaignReplayRecorder`, which records one `ReplayLevelSegment` per level actually played (own file path/bonus flag/gameplay seed/AST hash/difficulty/gore/carryover/frames) and stays the same instance across `advanceToNextLevel`'s auto-chain, only starting fresh on a genuinely new run (no carryover, or none in memory e.g. right after a reload). `ReplayPayload` bumped to `version: 2` (a `levels[]` array) — old single-level (`version: 1`) entries are deliberately left unsupported rather than migrated, and defensively hidden from the "Watch Replay" button rather than trusted blindly, since that shape round-tripped through `localStorage`/JSON and can't be trusted from the type alone. "Watch Replay" now walks the whole level sequence, re-locating/re-verifying/regenerating each in turn and carrying recorded state forward exactly like a live run. Verified in headless Chromium: a scripted 2-level recording produces correct per-level segments/carryover/hashes, and replaying it through fresh engines reproduces byte-identical final stats [Task 36]
- [x] replay just silently stopping was surprising, needs an "end of replay" dialog; also expose play/pause/seek/playback-speed controls — added `GameHud.showReplayEnded()`, shown (via a new `endReplay()` helper) for every non-win/death termination path: manual Escape stop, a file that can't be relocated/re-verified/parsed, and the (shouldn't-happen) frames-exhausted safety net; natural win/death still show their own Build Successful/Kernel Panic overlay as before. Fixed a real latent race while doing this: the drive loop could keep ticking (and, at a mid-campaign death, wrongly try to advance to the next level) between a level's engine firing onGameOver/onWin and the player actually dismissing that dialog — a new `levelEnded` flag now stops frame consumption the instant either fires, checked every tick and mid-burst. Also added a DOM transport bar (play/pause, seek back/forward ~5s, speed stepper 0.25x-4x) alongside the hint caption: pausing just stops consuming frames without cancelling the poll loop (so unpausing resumes on its own), speed changes how many recorded frames run per real tick via a fractional accumulator (each frame's own recorded `dt` is never altered, so the simulated trajectory itself never changes — only how fast it's watched), seeking forward bursts through recorded frames synchronously, and seeking backward — since simulation isn't reversible — rebuilds the current level's engine from scratch and bursts forward to the target instead. Verified in headless Chromium: restarting and re-bursting to the same target frame reproduces byte-identical state every time [Task 37]
