- [x] TODOs in the code do "something" with the level, to be determined — a `TODO`/`FIXME` marker in a comment (`isTodoFlagged`, exported from `astUtils.ts`) now bypasses the lore-terminal length/multi-line gate entirely, so even a short one-line `// TODO: fix this` gets a terminal (the short one-liner is the most common real form of technical debt, so excluding it would miss most of what this feature is meant to surface). Each flagged terminal also gets a small "technical debt" encounter on the floor tile just inside its room: a per-instance seeded-`rng` roll (equal thirds) picks a timed spike trap, a proximity mine (both reusing `placeTraps`' existing shapes/mechanics and constants), or a weak "Bug" enemy (a synthetic `CodeEntity`, flat 10 HP — well under the normal 25 HP floor — purple-tinted via the existing `EntityKind` fallback color, no `sprites.ts` changes needed). Deliberately a *trap* or *mine*, not a `fillHazards`-style permanent acid pool — the candidate tile is exactly where the player has to stand to read the terminal, and a permanently-damaging tile there would make it painful to ever reach rather than just riskier; a trap/mine keeps a genuine safe approach. Never more than one of the three for the same terminal (occasionally none at all, if no free adjacent floor tile exists — a best-effort placement, same philosophy as every other "extra thing near a room" system in this generator), and normal (non-flagged) long comments are completely unaffected. Verified in headless Chromium against the real parser + `MapGenerator`: a synthetic short `// TODO` comment survives the length gate, produces a terminal, and gets at most one adjacent trap/mine/enemy; regenerating from the same parsed AST is deterministic; a normal long comment still gets a terminal with no extra encounter. Follow-up: added the proximity mine as a third possible outcome (was trap-or-enemy only) — sampled 40 synthetic TODO comments across varying seeds and confirmed all three outcomes actu