- [x] files with shebang and no extension arent recognized as source — `registry.ts`'s `getParserForFilename`/`isParsable` now take an optional `sourceText`; when a filename has no extension, they sniff its leading `#!` line (`shebangExtension`) and map the interpreter basename (`bash`/`sh`/`zsh`/`python`/`python3`/`ruby`/`php`/`node`, trailing version numbers like `python3.11` or `bash5` stripped) onto whichever registered extension already has an adapter for it — this never adds a language, it just lets an existing adapter match a file with no extension of its own. `parseFile` already had the text in hand, so it just forwards it through. Fixed at both places a filename used to get judged on its name alone: `handleFileSelected` (clicking a file in the sidebar) now passes the just-read text, and `flattenParsableFiles` — the campaign-wide list behind "next level", entrypoint detection, and resume-save matching — is now `async` and reads content (only for the extensionless case) via a new `isParsableNode` helper before deciding; every caller in `main.ts` threads the `await` through. An interpreter this doesn't recognize (e.g. Perl, no adapter) still correctly reports not-parsable, and a real extension always wins over any shebang. Verified via the project's Vite-dev-server headless-Chromium recipe (needed because the parser layer imports tree-sitter grammar wasm through `?url`): 11 assertions against the real `registry.ts` covering a bare `#!/bin/bash`, `#!/usr/bin/env python3`, `#!/usr/bin/env ruby`, versioned interpreters, an unrecognized interpreter, a real extension overriding a misleading shebang, and `parseFile` itself succeeding end-to-end for an extensionless Python script — all passed [Task 41]
- [x] lore should ignore license headers — `astUtils.ts`'s `extractLargeComments` now runs a new `isLicenseHeader(text, startLine)` check first, ahead of (and overriding) the existing TODO-bypass/length/multi-line gate, so a comment can never become a lore terminal if it (a) sits within the first 10 lines of the file and (b) matches one of a broad set of license/copyright phrase patterns — this project's own SPDX+Copyright convention, plus common full-header boilerplate (MIT's "Permission is hereby granted", BSD's "Redistribution and use...", the GPL family, Apache). Without this, this repo's own 2-line header (the copyright line alone clears the 60-char lore threshold) would generate a lore terminal in nearly every file if the game were pointed at its own source; the same applies to any third-party repo carrying a standard license header. Deliberately position-gated to the first 10 lines only, so a genuinely long lore-worthy comment deep in a file that happens to mention "copyright" in prose is unaffected. Verified via the project's Vite-dev-server headless-Chromium recipe against the real `parseFile`: this repo's own SPDX+Copyright header, a synthetic MIT-style header, and a TODO-flagged copyright header all correctly produced zero lore comments; a license-y phrase placed past line 10 and an ordinary long comment both still correctly produced a lore comment as before [Task 42]
