- [x] privacy doc, what exactly happens with the workspace selected and what is stored on your machine — added `doc/user/privacy.md`, verified directly against source rather than assumed: grepped the whole codebase for every `fetch`/`XMLHttpRequest`/`WebSocket`/`localStorage`/cookie/analytics call. Only remote calls in the entire app are the opt-in GitHub loader (`src/fs/github.ts`): unauthenticated `GET`s to `api.github.com` (repo/tree metadata) and `raw.githubusercontent.com` (lazy per-file content fetch), triggered only by the "Load from GitHub" tab — a locally-picked workspace never touches the network, and neither does a custom BGM folder (played from a local object URL). Documented every `localStorage` key (`codeenstein-campaign-save`, `codeenstein-highscores`, `codeenstein-gore-level`, `codeenstein-difficulty`, the three volume keys) and exactly what each holds — confirmed the campaign save and replay system never store file *contents*, only workspace-relative paths, an AST SHA-256 hash, and recorded player *input*, not source code. No analytics/telemetry/crash-reporting library exists in `package.json` (only dependency is `web-tree-sitter`) or anywhere in `src`. Linked from the `doc/user` index.
- [x] dev docs, GDD, design descisions etc in `doc/dev` — added four files: `doc/dev/README.md` (index), `architecture.md` (the fs→parser→map→engine layering and its hard rules — ParsedFile as the only cross-layer contract, the "Enemy stays data" rule, why difficulty.ts/prng.ts live at src/ root, the determinism/replay constraint — every claim re-verified against current source doc-comments, not assumed), `game-design.md` (developer-facing "why" behind the code→dungeon mapping, enemy/difficulty/economy/scoring intent, distinct from doc/user/mechanics.md's player-facing "how"), and `decisions.md` (a themed, evergreen reference of notable tradeoffs/reversals — determinism, entrypoint detection, pack-vs-elite scaling, storage-quota handling, loot gating, feature reversals, dependency minimalism, doc transparency — citing this file's task numbers for full detail rather than restating them, explicitly not a copy of this log). Root `README.md` gained one line in its Documentation section linking to the new index; `doc/user` and this file were left untouched. Deliberately kept to four files rather than an ADR-per-decision structure, to stay maintainable as this backlog keeps growing.
- [x] fixme triggered mines are sometimes placed so close to the spawn point that it results in insta-damage — root cause: every hazard-placement system in `mapGenerator.ts` (`placeTraps`, `placePillars`, `placeAmmoPickups`) already keeps a minimum distance from spawn, but the TODO/FIXME "technical debt" encounter (`placeTodoEncounter`, spawns a spike trap, proximity mine, or weak "Bug" enemy next to a flagged comment's lore terminal) never checked distance to spawn at all — a comment physically located in the spawn room (room 0) could land its encounter immediately adjacent to the player, and a mine's 0.9s fuse or an already-mid-cycle spike trap could then deal damage before the player could realistically react. Fixed generally, not just for mines, per explicit ask: `spawn` is now threaded through `placeLoreTerminals` → `placeTodoEncounter`, which filters its candidate tiles to those at least `TRAP_SPACING` (3 tiles) from spawn — the exact same constant/`dist()` check `placeTraps`' own `farEnough` already uses — before rolling spike/mine/enemy; if every candidate is too close, the encounter is skipped entirely (matching the function's existing "never a hard failure" contract). Verified directly: a synthetic-`ParsedFile` harness piling TODO/FIXME comments into the spawn room across 300 distinct seeds reproduced the bug constantly pre-fix (dozens of mines/spikes/enemies landing 0-2 tiles from spawn) and confirmed zero violations post-fix across the same 300 seeds (2541 total hazard/encounter placements checked) [Task 51]
- [x] if player collects an unlockable weapon he already has, it should add its ammotype instead of being "wasted" — a weapon drop's `weaponIndex` is only guaranteed unowned at the moment an Elite dies (`dropEliteLoot` only rolls from `UNLOCKABLE_WEAPONS.filter` on what's still missing), not at the later moment the player actually walks over the drop — a second Elite's weapon drop can sit on the ground until the player has already unlocked that same weapon from a different one in the meantime. `applyLoot`'s `"weapon"` case (`engine.ts`) now checks `ownedWeapons.has(drop.weaponIndex)` first: already-owned resolves to an elite-sized ammo top-up of that weapon's `ammoType` instead (bullets for gdb, rockets for ghidra, via the same `scaledLootAmount` difficulty scaling every other pickup uses) rather than a no-op re-add-to-set-and-switch-weapon; not-yet-owned keeps the original unlock-and-equip behavior unchanged. Added `ELITE_ROCKETS_DROP_AMOUNT` (`loot.ts`) alongside the existing `ELITE_BULLETS_DROP_AMOUNT`/`ELITE_SWAP_DROP_AMOUNT`, since no elite-sized rockets fallback existed yet. Verified with `tsc --noEmit` [Task 52]
- [x] show proper introscreen when no workspace is loaded instead of the current minimal text, what this is, how it works, etc — replaced the single-line placeholder `<p>` in `#viewport` (`index.html`) with a static `#intro-screen`: a title/lede pulled from the README's pitch, a "How it works" code→dungeon mapping list (folder→level, file→room, function→enemy scaled by complexity, global var→acid pool, private/protected method→locked door, goto/label→teleporter, large comment→lore terminal, dead code→secret room), a "What you'll do" combat/campaign summary, and a "Privacy" card (per explicit follow-up request) stating plainly that a local workspace is parsed entirely client-side via WebAssembly and never leaves the machine, that the only network calls are the opt-in GitHub tab's, and linking out to the existing `doc/user/privacy.md` for full detail — wording double-checked against that doc rather than asserted from scratch, so it doesn't overclaim (e.g. doesn't say "never talks to the network" outright, since GitHub loading genuinely does). Pure static markup, no new JS — `launchLevel`'s existing "clear every `#viewport` child but the canvas" logic already removes it the moment a level launches, same as the old placeholder did; `resetToFileTree`'s separate "pick a file" placeholder (shown once a workspace *is* loaded but no file selected yet) was left untouched since the ask was specifically the no-workspace state. New `.intro-*` rules in `style.css` reuse the existing dark/monospace theme (`--bg-panel`/`--border`/`--accent`/`--muted`) with a responsive `auto-fit` two-card grid that collapses to one column on narrow windows, and `overflow-y: auto` so it scrolls within `#viewport` instead of clipping against the pre-existing `overflow: hidden`. Verified visually via Playwright (already a project devDependency) against the real dev server at both a wide (1400px) and narrow (900px) viewport — renders correctly, no console errors, single-column collapse confirmed at the narrow width [Task 53].
- [x] control info in the windowed ui below the canvas looks like shit — the whole thing used to be one long run-on `<p class="map-caption">` sentence mixing the level objective, gameplay tips, and every keybinding into undifferentiated 12px muted text. Split it apart: the caption now only carries the level path/objective and gameplay tips (shorter, no longer interleaved with keybindings), and a new `src/ui/controlsLegend.ts` renders the actual key/mouse/gamepad bindings as a row of keycap-styled chips (bordered, `--bg-panel`-backed `<span>`s that visually read as physical keys) grouped by action, plus — per explicit follow-up request for "even a graphic, showing the keyboard and key mapping" — a small literal WASD/QE cluster graphic (two offset rows of keycaps mimicking the physical keyboard stagger) with its own Move/Strafe/Turn legend, instead of just more prose. New `.controls-legend`/`.key`/`.key-cluster`/`.controls-chip` rules in `style.css` reuse the existing dark/monospace theme tokens (`--bg-panel`/`--border`/`--text`/`--muted`), no new palette colors introduced. Wired into `launchLevel` in `main.ts` only (the replay-viewing hint is a different, purely status-text caption and was left untouched). No keybindings changed, only how they're displayed — `doc/user/controls.md` was already accurate and needed no edit. Verified visually via Playwright against the real dev server: loaded the real `mcdope/codeenstein3d` GitHub repo end-to-end, confirmed the legend renders correctly both on the briefing screen and during actual live gameplay alongside the native canvas HUD, no console errors [Task 54].
- [x] code parsing / world generation should show a loading screen or indicator, for large repos it can take a while (to test: use any linux kernel git like `torvalds/linux`) — a workspace load previously gave no feedback in the main viewport at all: a fetched-but-unparsed tree, the up-to-4s entrypoint content-scan (`findEntrypoint`/`ENTRYPOINT_DETECTION_TIMEOUT_MS`), and the synchronous `MapGenerator.generate` call all ran with nothing but a one-line sidebar status (`#workspace-name`) changing, so a slow remote fetch just looked frozen. Added a `#loading-screen` overlay (spinner + status line, static markup in `index.html` alongside `#intro-screen`) shown via new `showLoadingScreen()`/`setLoadingStatus()` helpers in `main.ts`, wired into all three workspace-load entry points (Select Workspace, Load from GitHub, Continue Run) and `autoLaunchInitialLevel`, with the status text tracking each real phase: "Reading/Fetching…" → "Scanning for entrypoint…" → "Parsing `<file>`…" → "Generating world…". That last transition is followed by one `yieldToMainThread()` tick so the browser actually paints "Generating world…" before the synchronous, CPU-bound map generation call blocks the thread — chunking generation itself into an interruptible/async pass was considered but rejected as out of scope and risky given the project's determinism/replay constraints (see `doc/dev/architecture.md`). Also fixed a latent, unrelated-but-adjacent gap found while wiring the "nothing launched" path: `autoLaunchInitialLevel` finishing with no target (empty workspace, or every candidate failed to parse) previously left the viewport stuck on the stale intro screen instead of falling back to the "select a file" placeholder — factored that placeholder out of `resetToFileTree` into a shared `showFileTreePlaceholder()` so both paths use it. `doc/user/getting-started.md` gained one sentence on the "Picking a workspace" step describing the indicator. Verified visually via Playwright against the real dev server: captured the overlay mid-flight (network-throttled via a CDP session to make the phases observable) showing correct status-text transitions through fetch → scan phases, and confirmed the un-throttled path fully resolves — overlay disappears, canvas un-hides, briefing screen with the Task 54 controls legend renders — end-to-end against the real `mcdope/codeenstein3d` GitHub repo [Task 55].
- [x] reorder weapon hotkeys - 3 is unused because it was the knife once. there should be no "holes" between the hotkeys — root cause: `WEAPONS` (`weapons.ts`) is ordered `[pistol, shotgun, knife, gdb, ghidra]` and number keys used to map straight onto that raw array index, but the knife is structurally excluded from number-key switching (`canWieldViaNumberKey` — it's bound to Left-Ctrl instead), so key `3` (→ index 2, the knife) was permanently dead while gdb/ghidra sat at `4`/`5` instead of `3`/`4`. Fixed without touching `WEAPONS`' own array order (which would've silently corrupted every persisted `weaponIndex`/`ownedWeapons` numeric value in campaign saves, replays, and highscore entries — a real hazard considered and rejected): added `NUMBER_KEY_WEAPONS`, a derived `WEAPONS`-index list filtered to just the non-melee entries in array order (`[0,1,3,4]`), and `RaycasterEngine`'s number-key handling now looks up `NUMBER_KEY_WEAPONS[slot]` instead of treating the pressed digit's slot as a raw array index — so `1`/`2`/`3`/`4` land on pistol/shotgun/gdb/ghidra contiguously, and `5`+ stay harmless no-ops exactly like they always were past the last real slot. Mousewheel cycling (`cycleWeapon`) was already correct (iterates raw `WEAPONS` indices directly, independent of the number-key mapping) and needed no change. Updated `doc/user/mechanics.md`'s weapon-slot table (gdb 4→3, ghidra 5→4) to match. Verified against the real dev server via Playwright: loaded `mcdope/codeenstein3d`, typed the `IDKFA` cheat to own every weapon, then confirmed via captured console fire-logs (turning away from spawn first so a shot reliably misses rather than landing an ambiguous enemy hit) that pressing `3` now fires as `[gdb]` and pressing `4` now fires as `[ghidra] launched` — both previously unreachable at those keys [Task 56].
- [x] gdb should have its own bullets, and their drops should have a suited amount of ammo. 10 bullets in an mp5 doesnt makes sense. should also cause more dmg to the enemy — gdb used to share the `"bullets"` ammo pool with the pistol/shotgun; split into its own `"smg"` pool (new `AmmoType`/`LootKind` member) with its own HUD readout ("SMG AMMO", gdb's blue), starting reserve (`STARTING_SMG_AMMO = 40`, a flat carry-forward reserve like rockets since gdb itself has to be earned), regular drop size (`SMG_DROP_AMOUNT = 30`, a magazine-sized amount instead of the old shared 6-bullet drop that emptied in under a second at gdb's ~11 rounds/sec), and elite-kill-already-owned top-up (`ELITE_SMG_DROP_AMOUNT = 80`). Loot-roll weights (`LOOT_WEIGHTS`/`NORMAL_LOOT_WEIGHTS`/`BONUS_LOOT_WEIGHTS`) rebalanced to add an smg share (gated out entirely until gdb is owned, mirroring the existing rockets/launcher gate); `rollLoot` gained a `hasGdb` parameter for that gate. `damagePerPellet` bumped 7→11 (~57% more) per the explicit ask — still below the pistol's 25/shotgun's per-shot burst, but a meaningful step up given gdb's ~11 shots/sec ceiling. Threaded `smg` through the full ammo lifecycle the same way `bullets`/`rockets` already were: `EngineStats`/`EngineCarryover`, the IDKFA cheat (maxes all three pools now), `fire()`'s ammo check/deduction, `CampaignSave`/`loadCampaignSave` (defaults missing `smg` to 0 for saves written before this field existed — a resumed run with gdb already unlocked just starts it dry, not broken), and `computeScore`'s ammo-remaining bonus (now a three-way average across bullets/rockets/smg instead of two). Deliberately did *not* thread a parallel `hasGdb` gate through `mapGenerator.generate`'s statically-placed `AmmoPickup`s (`placeAmmoPickups`/`placeSecretRooms` stay bullets/rockets-only) — those are explicitly documented as "a backup source, not the primary one," and adding it would have meant changing `generate()`'s signature at both call sites for a source that barely matters next to kill drops; smg ammo is acquired via kill drops only. `doc/user/mechanics.md`, `doc/dev/game-design.md`, and `doc/dev/decisions.md`'s "Ammo/Loot Gating" theme updated to match. Verified against the real dev server via Playwright: loaded `mcdope/codeenstein3d`, typed `IDKFA`, confirmed the HUD switches to a distinct "SMG AMMO" readout when gdb is equipped (separate from `BULLETS`), that holding fire on gdb (auto-fire is `isFireHeld()`-gated, not edge-triggered — a bare `press()` can land entirely between sampled frames, so held it down for real across several frames) drained only the smg pool (999→996 over three ~0.09s-interval shots), and that switching back to the pistol showed `BULLETS` still at its own untouched cheat-maxed value — full pool separation confirmed live, not just by code review [Task 57].
- [x] add "(Build: $date $time)" in title — added a `buildTimestamp()` helper in `vite.config.ts` (`YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM`, local to the build machine) injected into the bundle as a `__BUILD_TIME__` global via Vite's `define`, ambient-declared in `vite-env.d.ts`. `main.ts` stamps it onto `document.title` (`🔫 Codeenstein 3D (Build: ...)`) right after imports — mainly so a stale cached bundle after a deploy is obvious from the tab itself rather than silently serving old code. For `npm run dev` this is "when the dev server started," not a live clock, since `define` is evaluated once when the Vite config loads. Verified both `npm run build` completes cleanly with the new `define` block and, via Playwright against the real dev server, that `document.title` actually contains a correctly-formatted `(Build: YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM)` [Task 58].
- [x] canvas should fill as much of the window as possible while keeping aspect ratio — the canvas was capped at `width: min(100%, 960px)`, a fixed max-width that left a lot of a wide monitor unused. Tried a pure-CSS `width:auto; height:auto; max-width:100%; max-height:100%; aspect-ratio:640/400;` fix first and it didn't work: `width:auto` on a replaced element like `<canvas>` falls back to its *intrinsic* size (the 640×400 `width`/`height` attributes) rather than growing to fill available space — `max-width`/`max-height` only ever let it *shrink*, never grow, so the canvas stayed pinned at ~640×400 regardless of window size. Replaced with a JS-driven fit: the canvas is now wrapped in a new `canvasArea` flex-grow `<div>` (absorbs whatever vertical space `#viewport`'s other children — hint caption, controls legend, replay transport bar — don't need) and a `fitCanvasToArea()` function in `main.ts` reads `canvasArea`'s actual content-box size and sets the canvas's inline `width`/`height` in px to the largest 640:400 box that fits inside it, wired up via a `ResizeObserver` on `canvasArea` (fires automatically on window resizes *and* on `canvasArea.hidden` flipping false at a level launch — no explicit call needed at each call site). Also moved `canvas.hidden` toggling to `canvasArea.hidden` throughout (`showLoadingScreen`, `launchLevel`, `showFileTreePlaceholder`, `startReplay`) — hiding an *ancestor* of the Fullscreen API's target element ends fullscreen the same way hiding the element itself does, so this preserves the exact same "leaving the game ends fullscreen, a level transition doesn't" timing the old `canvas.hidden` comment described. `fitCanvasToArea()` is a no-op while `canvas` is actually the fullscreen element (checked via `document.fullscreenElement === canvas`), leaving `.scene-canvas:fullscreen`'s existing CSS to own that state entirely — turned out to be a redundant-but-harmless guard in practice, since the Fullscreen API's UA-level top-layer sizing overrides any inline style regardless, confirmed by direct testing. Verified via Playwright against the real dev server: measured the canvas's actual rendered size at 1920×1080 (1292×808, aspect ratio exactly 1.600 — previously would have capped at 960×600), 1400×900 (772×483), and 1024×700 (396×248) windows, confirmed `canvasArea` genuinely flex-grows via computed-style inspection (not just eyeballing), and confirmed fullscreen enter (fills the full viewport) and exit (cleanly reverts to the fitted size) both still work correctly [Task 59].
- [x] ghidra causes WAY to less dmg - i had to use 2 rockets on some enemies, thats ridicolous considering its a rocket launcher — root cause was purely numeric: a regular (non-pack, non-Elite) enemy's HP scales with its function's complexity (`HP_PER_COMPLEXITY = 25` per point, up to `ELITE_COMPLEXITY_THRESHOLD = 40` before it splits into a pack or becomes an Elite instead), so even a single, unremarkable function with complexity 3-9 already sits at 75-225 HP — routinely above ghidra's old 70 ground-zero `damagePerPellet`, and a direct/near hit rarely even reaches that max once `rocketDamageAt`'s distance falloff is applied. Bumped `damagePerPellet` 70 → 100 (`weapons.ts`), still felt weak in a second playtest pass — bumped again to 150. Blast radius/falloff floor/ammo cost/cooldown all left untouched both times, so this is purely "hits harder," not "hits farther or cheaper" (note: this does mean point-blank self-splash is now more dangerous too, an intentional side effect of the existing "standing too close to your own blast still hurts you" risk/reward design, not a new bug). Verified with `tsc --noEmit`; no other file hardcoded the old damage numbers [Task 60].

